"""The model comparison process was structured around a key clinical priority: addressing the severe class imbalance to prevent pathological patients from escaping diagnosis. For this reason, the analysis discarded misleading metrics such as standard accuracy, favoring the Macro F1-Score and, above all, Balanced Accuracy, calculated through rigorous five-fold Nested Cross-Validation to validate the operational stability of each algorithm. Although Random Forest returned the highest F1-Score, rewarding overall caution, the Precision-Recall Operating Points graph unequivocally clarified the true clinical trade-offs of the various classifiers, proving to be the most powerful visual tool of the entire analysis. This representation visually demonstrated how Random Forest adopts an overly conservative approach, ensuring high precision but compromising sensitivity. Conversely, Logistic Regression dominated the Recall axis, clearly advancing: thanks to the application of a global mathematical penalty for class balancing, the model was forced not to ignore minority categories. The result is an algorithm capable of intercepting the largest possible number of diabetic and pre-diabetic subjects, sacrificing only a minimal fraction of reliability against false alarms. In a preventive screening context, where a missed diagnosis has far more serious consequences than an additional screening test, this exceptional performance balance, combined with the complete medical transparency of its coefficients, justifies and mathematically validates the selection of Logistic Regression as the definitive model for this study."""

# 1. Select the Balanced Accuracy scores for the two main contenders
# We compare our chosen model (LR) against the best performer in F1 (RF)
model_a_scores = ba_scores_dict['Logistic Regression']
model_b_scores = ba_scores_dict['Random Forest']

# 2. Execute the Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test
# This test checks if the median of the differences between the two groups is zero
stat, p_value = wilcoxon(model_a_scores, model_b_scores)

print("=== WILCOXON SIGNED-RANK TEST (Balanced Accuracy) ===")
print(f"Comparison: Logistic Regression vs Random Forest")
print(f"Test Statistic: {stat:.3f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value:.4f}")

# 1. Select the Balanced Accuracy scores for the top two performers on this metric
# Logistic Regression (1st) vs XGBoost (2nd)
lr_ba_scores = ba_scores_dict['Logistic Regression']
xgb_ba_scores = ba_scores_dict['XGBoost']

# 2. Execute the Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test
# This is a non-parametric test for paired samples (the same 5 CV folds)
stat_lr_xgb, p_value_lr_xgb = wilcoxon(lr_ba_scores, xgb_ba_scores)

print("=== WILCOXON SIGNED-RANK TEST (Balanced Accuracy) ===")
print(f"Comparison: Logistic Regression vs XGBoost")
print(f"Test Statistic: {stat_lr_xgb:.3f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value_lr_xgb:.4f}")

"""Wilcoxon tests performed on Balanced Accuracy returned a p-value of 0.0625 for the comparisons between Logistic Regression vs. Random Forest and Logistic Regression vs. XGBoost. Although this value is slightly higher than the conventional threshold of 0.05, it represents the minimum value (maximum significance) achievable with a sample size of only 5 folds. The fact that the test statistic is equal to 0.000 indicates that Logistic Regression outperformed the other models in every single iteration of the cross-validation.

#**FINAL MODEL TUNING AND TRAINING**
"""

# 1. Define the machine learning pipeline
# Standardize features by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance,
# then apply multinomial Logistic Regression configured for imbalanced data.
final_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('model', LogisticRegression(
        multi_class='multinomial',
        solver='lbfgs',
        class_weight='balanced',
        random_state=42,
        max_iter=2000
    ))
])

# 2. Define the hyperparameter grid for tuning
# Testing different values for the regularization strength 'C' (smaller values = stronger regularization)
param_grid = {
    'model__C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100]
}

# 3. Setup the cross-validation strategy
# Use StratifiedGroupKFold to preserve class distribution across folds
# and ensure that the same group does not appear in both train and validation sets.
final_cv = StratifiedGroupKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=SEED)

# 4. Initialize GridSearchCV
# Search for the best hyperparameters using the defined pipeline and cross-validation,
# optimizing for 'balanced_accuracy' due to class imbalance.
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=final_pipeline,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=final_cv,
    scoring='balanced_accuracy',
    verbose=1,
    n_jobs=-1
)

# 5. Run the grid search
# Fit the model over the grid, explicitly passing the 'groups' parameter for cross-validation splitting
grid_search.fit(X, y, groups=groups)

# 6. Extract the Best Results
best_hparams = grid_search.best_params_
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

print(f"Best Hyperparameters: {best_hparams}")
print(f"Best Balanced Accuracy Score: {grid_search.best_score_:.4f}")

# 7. Final Parameters (Coefficients)
# Extract feature names from the original dataframe
feature_names = X.columns

logistic_regression_step = best_model.named_steps['model']

# Create a clear DataFrame for the coefficients
# In multiclass Logistic Regression, coef_ has shape (n_classes, n_features)
coef_df = pd.DataFrame(
    logistic_regression_step.coef_,
    columns=feature_names,
    index=['Healthy (Class 0)', 'Pre-Diabetes (Class 1)', 'Diabetes (Class 2)']
)

print("\n--- Final Model Parameters (Coefficients) ---")
# We transpose (.T) the DataFrame to make it easier to read (Features as rows)
display(coef_df.T)

# Print the Intercepts
print("\n--- Final Model Intercepts ---")
intercept_df = pd.DataFrame(
    logistic_regression_step.intercept_,
    index=['Healthy (Class 0)', 'Pre-Diabetes (Class 1)', 'Diabetes (Class 2)'],
    columns=['Intercept']
)
display(intercept_df)

# Extract detailed results from the Grid Search
cv_results = grid_search.cv_results_

# Extract the tested C values and their corresponding metrics (Balanced Accuracy)
c_values = np.array(cv_results['param_model__C'].data, dtype=float)
mean_scores = cv_results['mean_test_score'] # This is the mean metric across inner folds
std_scores = cv_results['std_test_score']   # Standard deviation to observe stability

# --- PLOT CREATION (VALIDATION CURVE) ---
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plot the main line for the mean scores
plt.plot(c_values, mean_scores, marker='o', linestyle='-', color='teal', linewidth=2, markersize=8, label='Mean Balanced Accuracy')

# Add a shaded area to represent variance (standard deviation)
plt.fill_between(c_values, mean_scores - std_scores, mean_scores + std_scores, alpha=0.2, color='teal')

# Axes formatting
plt.xscale('log') # CRUCIAL to properly space out values like 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1...
plt.xlabel("Regularization Strength 'C' (Log Scale)", fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel("Balanced Accuracy (Cross-Validation)", fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.title("Validation Curve: Hyperparameter 'C' Optimization for Logistic Regression", fontsize=14, pad=15)

# Grid and Legend for better readability
plt.grid(True, which="both", ls="--", alpha=0.6)
plt.legend(loc='lower right', fontsize=11)

# Highlight the winning parameter with a red dot
